FONT><BR><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>(</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#FFFFFF>11/21/00</FONT> <FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#FFFFFF>10:32:28 am</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>)<BR></FONT><A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fpaladinsofnorrathwhatisapaladin.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=86.topic><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>Reply</FONT></A></TD><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT><B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">What is the role of a Paladin?</font></B><HR><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">Greetings. I am Vaalar Valorian, a lvl 24 Paladin of Mithaniel Marr on Saryn.<br>
<br>
I started this character on February 2nd, 2000 with a total of 10 days, 13 hours played. The time in between has been spent levelling a Erudite Wizard to 21 and Human Monk to 21. There have numerous other characters, to many to remember, that have long since retired into obscurity.<br>
<br>
When I play the Wizard or Monk, both are agnostic, I really don't think twice about the content or make-up of any pickup group that I happen to join. They are in it for the adventure and the knowledge to be gained; as well as the fame and fortune. With Vaalar it is a different story. You see the single driving factor in my constant return to this character is the need, through a fantasy environment, to express my desire to make a difference. To be the one who stands behind his principles and seek out to do battle with all the evil that plagues this land. This need is not easily expressed, especially within the game environment. <br>
<br>
Back when Vaalar was lvl 21 and hunting in South Karana, I joined pickup groups and got caught up in the  levelling and gaining good loot cycle - need better armour and weapons; need to make more coin; need to level to get out of this crazy place. For a brief moment in time, between the carnage, I stopped and looked at my group members; HIGH ELF CLERIC, ERUDITE PALADIN, HALF ELF PALADIN (ME), DARK ELF WIZARD and TROLL SHADOW KNIGHT, and thought, &quot;Oh my god! What am I doing here killing these innocent birds with these people! Two of which are evil&quot;. I informed them of my need to leave and disbanded.<br>
<br>
Since then I relocated to Kunark and have been soloing in Lake of Ill Omen, where I made 24 last night. At least over here most MOB's are evil in nature and I can do justice by killing them. Hunting here is fine, pickup groups with good-evil mix are the problem. Throw in the Iksar and it really gets confusing - every pickup group is guaranteed to contain someone of evil alliance. Pondering this dilemma while meditating, I began to think about the role and even the goal of the different race/class combinations. Especially those of the three principles that I currently play; Paladin, Wizard and Monk.<br>
<br>
The Wizard and Monk (indifferent group) both basically have the same goal to achieve in this game; explore the land and gain personal power through knowledge and experience. What is the Paladin's role? What is his goal? Is it the same as for the Wizard and Monk, or is it to seek out and fight evil and lend a helping hand to those in need? If this is right, then we cannot group with evil, period. Otherwise it ceases to be what it should be and becomes just another game where the goal is get the best of everything regardless of the cost and subsequent loss of honour.<br>
<br>
I included the Monk in the indifferent group. I do this fresh from my Monk witnessing, last evening, Saryn's highest level monk (Human 60) kill Paladin Guards in North Freeport for sport, then leave their corpses to lay waste while the greedy denizens jostle and fight each other to be the first to loot them. Maybe I'm getting to old for all this, but it really struck a chord in me.<br>
<br>
My apologies for the long rambling post... but, the question is important, what is our role and how do we play it in an environment where most people do not care and look upon your role-playing as a hindrance and nuisance? Is it a Paladin's role to learn to become the best group member possible for the higher level raids, or is it to advance through the levels desperately trying to remain true to the ideal that first led you to become a Paladin in the first place?<br>
<br>
